us-bibliographic-data-application.invention-title: MIXED POWDER, METHOD OF VAPOR-DEPOSITING ORGANIC COMPOUND, METHOD OF FABRICATING ORGANIC ELECTROLUMINESCENCE DEVICE, METHOD OF SELECTING ORGANIC COMPOUNDS, AND METHOD OF VAPOR-DEPOSITING

abstract.p: A mixed powder usable for a vapor deposition process, including a first organic compound and a second organic compound, wherein the following formula (1) is satisfied:

|θ1−θ2|≥10° (1)
where
θ1: a spread angle of a vapor deposition trajectory when a powder consisting of the first organic compound is vapor-deposited on a base material from a vapor deposition source, and
θ2: a spread angle of a vapor deposition trajectory when a powder consisting of the second organic compound is vapor-deposited on a base material from a vapor deposition source.

description.heading: TECHNICAL FIELD
description.p: The invention relates to a mixed powder, a method of vapor-depositing an organic compound, a method of fabricating an organic electroluminescence device, a method of selecting an organic compound, and a method of vapor-depositing.
description.heading: BACKGROUND ART
description.p: Vacuum vapor deposition process is generally used as a method of forming an organic layer in various fields including organic semiconductor devices such as organic electroluminescence devices (hereinafter, also referred to as organic EL devices), organic transistors, organic solar cells, and the like. In this process, an organic layer is formed by heating a target material in a vapor deposition source (a crucible) to allow the material to melt-evaporate or sublimate, and depositing the vaporized material on a substrate placed above. For example, Patent Documents 1 and 2 disclose formation of an organic layer of an organic EL device by a vacuum vapor deposition process.

SUMMARY OF THE INVENTION
description.p: However, there are cases where some organic materials do not deposit sufficiently on a substrate, since they falls into a vapor deposition source or a vapor deposition equipment to block the vapor deposition source, or they precipitate in the vapor deposition equipment before reaching the substrate. In a mass-production deposition apparatus, a cylindrical cavity with a large inner diameter is sometimes installed at the top of the crucible for pressure control, but in this case as well, material deposits near a nozzle installed at the top of the cavity and inside the cavity, to cause problems such as crucible blockage.

An object of the invention is to provide a method of vapor-depositing and a mixed powder enabling an efficient vapor deposition which is hardly causing a process trouble even when an organic compound which is unsuitable for a vapor deposition process is used.

As a result of studies, the inventor found that the above-mentioned problems at the time of vapor deposition have a large relationship with a degree of spread (diffusion) of an organic material at the time when it is vaporized from a vapor deposition source, that is, a degree of spread in the lateral direction (width direction), i.e., a spread of a vapor deposition trajectory. In other words, in the case of a material with a small degree of spread during a vapor deposition, it is conceivable that the vaporized material is converged in a part of a substrate due to its high straight traveling property, the supply rate becomes faster than the deposition rate in the part of the substrate, and as a result, deposition on the substrate may become difficult. Also, when using the cylindrical cavity as described above, the vaporized material is reflected by the upper wall inside the cavity to deposit at the bottom of the cavity. On the other hand, in the case of a material with a large degree of spread during a vapor deposition, it is conceivable that a proportion of precipitation in the vapor deposition equipment without reaching the substrate is increased, also, when using the cylindrical cavity, a turbulence is generated inside the cavity, a velocity difference between the inside and outside of the nozzle is generated, thereby facilitating crystal growth at the edge of the nozzle.

As a result of further studies to solve the above-mentioned problems, the inventor found that when vapor deposition is performed using a mixed material (powder) previously prepared by mixing a material with a large degree of spread of a vapor deposition trajectory with a material with a small degree of spread of a vapor deposition trajectory, a degree of spread of a vapor deposition trajectory becomes smaller than the former and larger than the latter. Namely, the inventor found that the vapor deposition characteristics (a spread of a vapor deposition trajectory) of an organic material can be adjusted by mixing another organic material having a different vapor deposition characteristics. The inventor found that, by this means, an efficient vapor deposition which is less likely to cause process troubles becomes possible even when using an organic material which unsuitable for a vapor deposition process because of its too wide or too narrow vapor deposition trajectory in the case where it is used alone, and the inventor has completed the invention.

description.heading: MODE FOR CARRYING OUT THE INVENTION
[Method of Vapor-Depositing]
description.p: The method of vapor-depositing according to one aspect of the invention includes, when vapor-depositing a first organic compound (hereinafter, also referred to as a “first component”) from a vapor deposition source to a base material, adjusting a spread angle of a vapor deposition trajectory of the first organic compound by adding a second organic compound (hereinafter, also referred to as a “second component”) having a larger or smaller spread angle of a vapor deposition trajectory at the time of a vapor deposition than that of the first organic compound.

As described above, since the spread of a vapor deposition trajectory at the time of vapor deposition of the first organic compound can be changed by using another organic compound (a second organic compound) having different degree of spread of the a deposition trajectory in combination, the vapor deposition trajectory can be adjusted so as to have a desired degree of spread. Although the mechanism is not necessarily clear, it is considered to be due to intermolecular interactions of the first organic compound and the second organic compound.

For example, by mixing a first organic compound with a second organic compound having a smaller spread of a vapor deposition trajectory than that of the first organic compound, the spread of a vapor deposition trajectory when the mixture is used for a vapor deposition can be suppressed and narrowed compared with when the first organic compound is used alone for a vapor deposition. Also, by mixing a first organic compound with a second organic compound having a larger spread of a vapor deposition trajectory than that of the first organic compound, the vapor deposition trajectory when the mixture is used for vapor deposition can be widened compared when the first organic compound is used alone for a vapor deposition.

Thus, even when using a compound which is unsuitable for a vapor deposition process due to its too wide or too narrow vapor deposition trajectory in the case where it is used alone, blockage of crucible, undesired deposition, adhesion to a protective plate or the like can be prevented to reduce troubles in a vapor deposition process by adjusting (improving) the vapor deposition trajectory by combining another compound having different vapor deposition characteristics. In addition, a high-rate vapor deposition can be achieved while maintaining a balance between a vapor deposition rate and a precipitation rate, and mass production efficiency and a material usage efficiency can be increased.
Note that, as will be described below, in one embodiment, the first organic compound and the second organic compound are used in powder form.
description.heading: <Spread of Vapor Deposition Trajectory>
description.p: In the invention, the “spread of vapor deposition trajectory” refers to a degree to which a material vaporized with heating in a vapor deposition source spreads form the opening of the vapor deposition source when the vaporized material is ejected toward an opposite base material (e.g., a substrate) located above the vapor deposition source. Specifically, the degree is evaluated by the central angle θ of spread when the vapor deposition source is viewed from the horizontal direction. The method of measuring the central angle θ (spread angle θ of vapor deposition trajectory) is as follows.
description.heading: (Method of Measuring Spread Angle θ of Vapor Deposition Trajectory)
description.p: Hereinafter, a method of measuring a spread angle θA of a vapor deposition trajectory of an organic compound A to be measured will be described with reference to Drawings.
description.heading: (1) Measuring Apparatus
description.p: A crucible and a substrate to be vapor-deposited are placed inside a chamber of a vapor deposition equipment having a decompression function. At this time, as shown in FIG. 1(a), a crucible 101 is placed so that its longitudinal direction becomes vertical, and a substrate 102 is placed so that its surface to be vapor-deposited becomes perpendicular to the longitudinal direction of the crucible 101 (i.e., horizontal direction). When the central point of the crucible opening is defined as C0, and the intersection point of the line L0 extended from the central point C0 in the longitudinal direction of the crucible and the surface of the substrate to be vapor-deposited is defined as S0, the distance between C0-S0 is set to 50 mm.

As the vapor deposition source, a crucible made of aluminum nitride is used, the crucible has a cylindrical shape with one end closed (crucible having a cylindrical hollow part), an inner diameter of the hollow part of 10 mm, and a total length of the hollow part of 50 mm or more. The total length of the hollow part is set to be 100 mm or less.

Other conditions of the vapor deposition equipment are not particularly limited as long as the method of measuring can be performed. As the substrate, a glass substrate is generally used. The size and thickness of the substrate are not particularly limited as long as the method for measuring can be performed.
description.heading: (2) Method of Operation
description.p: As shown in FIG. 1(b), the crucible 101 is charged with a powder of an organic compound A (sample 103). The input amount of the powder is set to be 5% or more of the total length of the hollow part of the crucible, and is set not to exceed 20%. A bulky powder may be compressed.

The degree of vacuum in the chamber is set to be 1×10−3 Pa or less, and the crucible is heated to start evaporation of the organic compound A, so that the vapor pressure (saturated vapor pressure) P of the organic compound A obtained by the following formula (A1) becomes 1 Pa or more, and the film formation is continued while maintaining the above-mentioned conditions until the sample 103 is completely vaporized.
In the formula (A1), each symbol represents the followings:

P: Saturated vapor pressure [Pa]
A: Deposition area on the surface of the substrate [m2]
ΔW: Mass loss of the organic compound A in the vapor deposition source [kg]
T: Temperature of an evaporation surface at the vapor deposition source [K]
t: Time [sec]
M: Molecular weight of the organic compound A [kg/mol]
R: Gas constant [J/(mol·K)]

In the formula (A1), A (deposition area on the surface of the substrate [m2]) is an area of a circle having a radius of the minimum value of the distance between S0 to Sr, in which Sr is the position where the film thickness becomes 0.05 T0, wherein T0 is the film thickness at S0.
In the formula (A1), T (temperature of an evaporation surface in the vapor deposition source [K]) is the temperature of the crucible at the end of the vapor deposition.

Strictly theoretically, a condensation coefficient “a” may affect the saturated vapor pressure P, but in this operation, since the organic compound A is considered to be in a sufficiently spreaded state, the condensation coefficient “a” is deemed as 1. Therefore, the condensation coefficient “a” does not appear in the formula (A1).

When the heat of the heated crucible 101 is easily transmitted to the substrate 102, in order to prevent the negative effect of the heat, a reflector or the like may be placed around the opening of the crucible 101 for example so as to be parallel to the substrate 102 in a position that does not affect the vapor deposition trajectory.
description.heading: (3) Measurement of Film Thickness and Calculation of θA
description.p: For the film obtained on the substrate 102, the film thickness is measured along the vapor deposited surface of the substrate from S0 to evaluate the film thickness distribution.

The film thickness distribution in this example is shown in FIG. 2(a) (schematic diagram). When vacuum vapor deposition of an organic compound is performed onto a fixed substrate, such a film thickness distribution is generally obtained. Horizontal axis in FIG. 2(a) indicates a tilt angle θ from the center-line L0 around C0. As shown in FIGS. 2(a) and (b), when the film thickness at the angle θ=0° (film thickness at S0) is defined to be T0, and the angle at the position SA (∠S0C0SA) where the film thickness decreases to 25% to become 0.25 T0 is defined to be θa, the spread angle of the vapor deposition trajectory of the organic compound A is defined as θA=2θa in consideration of the spread in the lateral direction. Note that SA is a position where the distance from S0 is minimized.

The film thickness and the film thickness distribution can be measured by the method described in Example (a method by providing a mask on the substrate surface) and a method using an optical film thickness meter.

The above measurement can be carried out using a general vapor deposition equipment having a cylindrical crucible having one end closed (e.g., a film forming apparatus used in a fabrication of an organic EL device, etc.).
(Difference in spread angle θ)

In one embodiment, as the first organic compound and the second organic compound described above, organic compounds with a difference of 10° or more in a spread angle θ of a vapor deposition trajectory are used. This embodiment can be expressed as follows.
A method of vapor-depositing an organic compound comprising:

vaporizing a mixed powder comprising a first organic compound and a second organic compound from a vapor deposition source, to form a film on a base material opposite to the vapor deposition source, wherein the following formula (1) is satisfied for the mixed powder:
where
θ1: a spread angle of a vapor deposition trajectory when a powder consisting of the first organic compound is vapor-deposited on a base material from a vapor deposition source, and
θ2: a spread angle of a vapor deposition trajectory when a powder consisting of the second organic compound is vapor-deposited on a base material from a vapor deposition source.

If the difference between the spread angles θ of the vapor deposition trajectory of the two materials (|θ1-θ2|) is 10° or more, the above-mentioned effect of adjusting a spread of a vapor deposition trajectory is sufficiently expected, and a desired vapor deposition trajectory (a spread angle θm of a vapor deposition trajectory of a mixed powder) can be realized depending upon a vapor deposition equipment and required conditions.

For example, in the case where θm is adjusted to become a° smaller than θ1 to suppress a spread of a vapor deposition trajectory of a first organic compound, as a rough indication, a second organic compound having θ2 of about (θ1-2a)° can be combined to form a mixed powder having a desired θm with adjusting mixing ratio of the two compounds or the like.

The difference between the spread angles θ of the vapor deposition trajectory of two materials (|θ1-θ2|) is preferably 15° or more, and more preferably 20° or more. The larger the difference between θ1 and θ2 is, the wider the angle adjustment range becomes, and the desired θm can be easily obtained. The upper limit of the difference of the two θ's (|θ1-θ2|) is not particularly limited.

Although the actual values of θ1 and θ2 are not particularly limited, it is conceivable to combine, for example, a first organic compound having a θ1 of 100° to 120° with a second organic compound having a θ2 of 60° to 80° to form a mixed powder having a θm of 80° to 100°, by taking into consideration vapor deposition conditions in a conventional film forming apparatus.
description.heading: <Mixed Powder>
description.p: A mixed powder used in the method of vapor-depositing according to one aspect of the invention is not particularly limited as long as the mixed powder contains a powder of two kinds of organic compounds having different spread of a vapor deposition trajectory (preferably a powder of two kinds of organic compounds satisfying the formula (1)).

In one embodiment, it is preferred that the first organic compound and the second organic compound have compound characteristics similar to each other. The compound characteristics are, for example, a molecular weight, a sublimation temperature, a vapor deposition temperature, and the like.

A difference in molecular weight between the first organic compound and the second organic compound (|molecular weight of the first compound—molecular weight of the second compound|) is preferably 500 or less, more preferably 400 or less, and still more preferably 300 or less.

The evaporation temperature (sublimation temperature, vapor deposition temperature) of a compound is a temperature measured at a surface located a set distance away from the vapor deposition source of the material to be vapor deposited at a vapor deposition rate of 0.5 to 2 Å/sec in a vacuum deposition apparatus, at a constant pressure of 5 Pa or less, or in a vacuum vessel holding a pressure of 1 Pa to 1×10−7 Pa.

A difference between the evaporation temperature T1 [° C.] of the first organic compound, and the deposition temperature T2 [° C.] of the second organic compound (|T1-T2|) is, for example, 35° C. or lower, 30° C. or lower, 25° C. or lower, 20° C. or lower, or 15° C. or lower, and is preferably 20° C. or lower or 15° C. or lower.
In one embodiment, the difference between T1 and T2 (|T1-T2|) is 10° C. or higher and 30° C. or lower, 5° C. or higher and 25° C. or lower, or 0° C. or higher and 20° C. or lower.
description.heading: (Mixing Ratio)
description.p: Mixing ratio of the first organic compound and the second organic compound in the mixed powder is not particularly limited, and can be appropriately determined by taking into consideration a mixing ratio in a vapor deposited film and a spread angle θm of a vapor deposition trajectory. The mixing ratio (mass ratio) of the first organic compound and the second organic compound is usually 1:99 to 99:1, and for example, 10:90 to 90:10.
description.heading: (First Organic Compound and Second Organic Compound)
description.p: The compound structure of a first organic compound and a second organic compound is not particularly limited, and any organic compound can be used as long as satisfying the above-described vapor deposition characteristics.

In one embodiment, the first organic compound and the second organic compound are organic semiconductor materials, e.g., a material for an organic EL device, a material for an organic transistor, or a material for an organic solar cell.
As a material for an organic EL device, a material described below in [Method of fabricating organic EL device] can be used.

In one embodiment, at least one of the first organic compound and the second organic compound is a fluorescent emitting compound that emits fluorescence. Examples of the compound include a dopant material used in an emitting layer of an organic EL device, and a material described below in [Method of fabricating organic EL device] can be used.

In one embodiment, at least one of the first organic compound and the second organic compound is a fluorescent emitting compound that emits fluorescence with a main peak wavelength of 500 nm or less. As such compounds, a “blue fluorescent emitting material” described below in [Method of fabricating organic EL device] can be used.

The method for measuring the main peak wavelength of a compound is described as follows. A sample of 5 μmol/L toluene solution of the compound to be measured is prepared, placed in a quartz cell, and the emission spectrum (vertical axis: emission intensity, horizontal axis: wavelength) of this sample is measured at room temperature (300 K). The emission spectrum can be measured by a spectrofluorometer (Device name: F-7000) manufactured by Hitachi High-Technology Science Corporation. In the emission spectrum, the peak wavelength of the emission spectrum where the emission intensity is the maximum is defined as the main peak wavelength.

In one embodiment, neither the first organic compound nor the second organic compound is a phosphorescent compound that emits phosphorescence. Examples of the phosphorescent compound include materials described below in [Method of fabricating organic EL device].

In one embodiment, the first organic compound is a host material for the emitting layer and the second organic compound is a dopant material for the emitting layer. It is preferable that the triplet energy T1 (H1) of the first organic compound and the triplet energy T1 (D1) of the second organic compound satisfy the following relation (mathematical formula 1).
T1(D1)>T1(H1) (mathematical formula 1)
The method of measuring a triplet energy T1 is described as follows.

A compound to be measured is dissolved in EPA (diethylether:isopentane:ethanol=5:5:2 (volume ratio)) in a concentration of 10−5 mol/L or higher and 10−4 mol/L or lower, and this solution is put in a quartz cell as a measurement sample. For this measurement sample, phosphorescent spectrum (the vertical axis: phosphorescence emission intensity, the horizontal axis: wavelength) is measured at a low temperature (77 [K]), a tangent line is drawn to the rising edge on the short wavelength side of this phosphorescence spectrum, and the energy quantity calculated through the following conversion expression (F1) based on the wavelength value λedge [nm] of the intersection point between the tangent line and the horizontal axis is defined as the triplet energy T1.
Conversion expression (F1): T1 [eV]=1239.85/λedge

The tangent to the rise of the phosphorescence spectrum close to the short-wavelength region is drawn as follows. While moving on a curve of the phosphorescence spectrum from the short-wavelength region to the maximum spectral value closest to the short-wavelength region among the maximum spectral values, a tangent is checked at each point on the curve toward the long-wavelength of the phosphorescence spectrum. An inclination of the tangent is increased along the rise of the curve (i.e., a value of the ordinate axis is increased). A tangent drawn at a point of the maximum inclination (i.e., a tangent at an inflection point) is defined as the tangent to the rise of the phosphorescence spectrum close to the short-wavelength region.

The maximum with peak intensity being 15% or less of the maximum peak intensity of the spectrum is not included in the above-mentioned maximum closest to the short-wavelength region. The tangent drawn at a point of the maximum spectral value being closest to the short-wavelength region and having the maximum inclination is defined as a tangent to the rise of the phosphorescence spectrum close to the short-wavelength region.

For phosphorescence measurement, a spectrophotofluorometer body F-4500 (manufactured by Hitachi High-Technologies Corporation) is usable. Any device for phosphorescence measurement is usable. A combination of a cooling unit, a low temperature container, an excitation light source and a light-receiving unit may be used for phosphorescence measurement.

a substituted or unsubstituted non-fused aromatic hydrocarbon ring including 10 to 30 ring carbon atoms,
a substituted or unsubstituted fused aromatic heterocycle including 9 to 30 ring atoms, or
a substituted or unsubstituted trivalent non-fused aromatic heterocycle including 5 or 6 ring atoms.
A-(L)n-Ar—CN (721)
In the formula (721),
A is

a substituted or unsubstituted fused aryl group including 10 to 30 ring carbon atoms,
a substituted or unsubstituted non-fused aryl group including 6 to 30 ring carbon atoms,
a substituted or unsubstituted fused heteroaryl group including 9 to 30 ring atoms, or
a substituted or unsubstituted non-fused heteroaryl group including 5 to 30 ring atoms.
L is

a substituted or unsubstituted fused arylene group including 10 to 30 ring carbon atoms,
a substituted or unsubstituted non-fused arylene group including 6 to 30 ring carbon atoms,
a substituted or unsubstituted fused heteroarylene group including 9 to 30 ring atoms, or
a substituted or unsubstituted non-fused heteroarylene group including 5 to 30 ring atoms.
n is an integer of 0 to 2.
When n is 0, L is a single bond.
When n is 2, two L's may be the same as or different from each other.
Ar is

a substituted or unsubstituted fused arylene group including 10 to 30 ring carbon atoms,
a substituted or unsubstituted non-fused arylene group including 6 to 30 ring carbon atoms,
a substituted or unsubstituted fused heteroarylene group including 9 to 30 ring atoms, or
a substituted or unsubstituted non-fused heteroarylene group including 5 to 30 ring atoms.

In one embodiment, one or more compounds selected from each of the following groups (Group 2A) to (Group 33A) may also be independently used as the first organic compound and the second organic compound. Note that the first organic compound and the second organic compound in this specification are not limited to one or more compounds independently selected from each of the following groups (Group 2A) to (Group 33A), and may not be one or more compounds independently selected from each of the following groups (Group 2A) to (Group 33A).

description.p: In one embodiment, one or more compounds selected from each of the following groups (Group 1B) to (Group 33B) may also be independently used as the first organic compound and the second organic compound. description.heading: (Other Components, etc.)
description.p: In one embodiment, the mixed powder may or may not contain a component other than the first organic compound.
In one embodiment, the mixed powder does not contain a phosphorescent emitting compound.
In one embodiment, the mixed powder does not contain a heavy metal complex.

In one embodiment, the mixed powder consists of the first component and the second component, or consists essentially of the first component and the second component. In the latter case, the mixed powder may contain inevitable impurities.

In one embodiment, the mixed powder contains the first component and the second component in an amount of 80% by mass or more, 90% by mass or more, 95% by mass or more, 99% by mass or more, 99.5% by mass or more, 99.9% by mass or more, 99.99% by mass or more, or 100% by mass.
description.heading: (Method of Producing Powder, Etc.)
description.p: The mixed powder may be composed of particles containing the first organic compound and the second organic compound in one particle, or may be a mixture composed of a powder of the first organic compound and a powder of the second organic compound.

As a method of producing a powder, for example, a method wherein the first organic compound and the second organic compound is pulverized and mixed using a mortar or the like, or a method wherein the first organic compound and the second organic compound is placed in a container or the like, heated and melted in a chemically inert environment, followed by cooling to an ambient temperature, and the obtained mixture may be pulverized by a mixer or the like to obtain a powder may be given. By the latter method, the first organic compound and the second organic compound can be mixed at the molecular level. As a result, the ratio of sublimation areas of both the compounds can be easily controlled to a desired range, and more uniform vapor deposition can be performed. In addition, it is possible to prevent a problem such as uneven mixing that may occur during conveyance of the mixed powder.
The mixed powder may be formed into pellets by compression molding.
description.heading: <Method of Vapor-Depositing and Conditions for Vapor Deposition>
description.p: In the method of vapor-depositing according to one aspect of the invention, the other conditions are not particularly limited, a general vapor deposition equipment and general conditions for vapor deposition may be employed, as long as the method includes a step of vaporizing the above-mentioned mixed powder from a single vapor deposition source to form a film on a surface to be vapor-deposited of an opposing base material located above the vapor deposition source.

Vapor deposition is usually carried out under vacuum (under a pressure lower than atmospheric pressure). The pressure inside the apparatus during the vapor deposition is preferably 5.0 Pa or lower, more preferably 1.0 Pa or lower. The heating temperature during the vapor deposition is usually 150° C. to 400° C., and preferably 200° C. to 350° C.

In the method of vapor-depositing according to one aspect of the invention, a mixed powder which is obtained by melt-mixing a powder of a first organic compound and a powder of a second organic compound to obtain a solidified material, and pulverizing the solidified material, may be used to the vapor deposition. By the use of the mixed powder obtained as described above, the ratio of sublimation areas of both the compounds can be easily adjusted to a desired range.
Alternatively, as described above, the mixed powder may be compressed in advance to form pellets, and the pellets may be put into a vapor deposition source to perform the vapor deposition.

In the method of vapor-depositing according to one aspect of the invention, the distance between the opening of a vapor deposition source and a base material (the distance between a vapor deposition source and a substrate, the distance between S—S) is, for example, 20 to 600 mm.
description.heading: <Applicable Technical Field>
description.p: The method of vapor-depositing according to one aspect of the invention can be applied to any technical field including vapor deposition of an organic compound to form a film, and can be applied to, for example, fabrication of organic semiconductor devices such as an organic EL device, an organic transistor, an organic solar cell, and the like. As an example, a method of fabricating an organic EL device using the method of vapor-depositing according to one aspect of the invention will be described below.
description.heading: [Method of Fabrication of Organic EL Device]
description.p: A method of fabricating an organic EL device according to one aspect of the invention is a method of fabricating an organic EL device including a cathode, an anode, and one or more organic layers including an emitting layer disposed between the cathode and the anode, which includes a step of vaporizing a mixed powder from a vapor deposition source to deposit at least one layer of the one or two or more organic layers, wherein
the mixed powder includes a first organic compound and a second organic compound, and the following formula (1) is satisfied for the mixed powder:
where
θ1: a spread angle of a vapor deposition trajectory when a powder consisting of the first organic compound is vapor-deposited on a base material from a vapor deposition source, and
θ2: a spread angle of a vapor deposition trajectory when a powder consisting of the second organic compound is vapor-deposited on a base material from a vapor deposition source.

The mixed powder and the method of vapor-depositing in the above method of fabrication are as described above in the method of vapor-depositing in one aspect of the invention. As the mixed powder, a first organic compound and a second organic compound which are materials for an organic EL device are used.
As the device configuration of the organic EL device, the structures obtained by stacking structures represented by each of the following (1) to (4) on a substrate are exemplified.

(1) anode/emitting layer/cathode
(2) anode/hole-transporting zone/emitting layer/cathode
(3) anode/emitting layer/electron-transporting zone/cathode
(4) anode/hole-transporting zone/emitting layer/electron-transporting zone/cathode
“/” indicates that the layers are stacked directly adjacent to each other.

The electron-transporting zone is a region composed of one, or two or more organic layers containing an electron-transporting compound (also referred to as an “electron-transport layer” and/or an “electron-injecting layer”), and the hole-transporting zone is a region composed of one, or two or more organic layers containing a hole-transporting compound (also referred to as a “hole-transporting layer” and/or a “hole-injecting layer”).

In the method of fabricating an organic EL device according to one aspect of the invention, at least one layer in the organic layers of the organic EL device is formed by a vapor deposition process using the mixed powder. The layer to be formed by the use of the mixed powder is not particularly limited, and may be any organic layer. Two or more layers of the organic layers may be formed by a vapor deposition process using the mixed powder.

Examples of the combinations of a first organic compound and a second organic compound [first organic compound, second organic compound] in the mixed powder used for the film formation of an organic layer include, but are not limited to, [a host material for an emitting layer, and a host material for an emitting layer], [a host material for an emitting layer, and a dopant material for an emitting layer], [a host material for an emitting layer, and a material for a hole-transporting layer], [a material for a hole-transporting layer, and a material for a hole-transporting layer], [a material for an electron-transporting layer, and a material for an electron-transporting layer], [a host material for an emitting layer, and a material for an electron-transporting layer], and the like. As the above-described host material for an emitting layer, a blue emitting host material for an emitting layer can be used, for example.

Note that the method of forming each layer other than the layer to be formed by the vapor deposition of the above-mentioned mixed powder is not particularly limited, and a method of film formation by a vacuum deposition process using a single material, a spin coating process, or the like can be used.
Each layer of the organic EL device will be described below.
description.heading: (Substrate)
description.p: A substrate is used as a support of an emitting device. As the material for the substrate, glass, quartz, plastics or the like can be used, for example. Further, a flexible substrate may be used. The “flexible substrate” means a bendable (flexible) substrate, and specific examples thereof include plastic substrates formed each of polycarbonate, polyvinyl chloride, and the like.
description.heading: (Anode)
description.p: For the anode formed on the substrate, metals, alloys, electrically conductive compounds, mixtures thereof, and the like, which have a large work function (specifically 4.0 eV or larger) are preferably used. Specific examples include indium oxide-tin oxide (ITO: Indium Tin Oxide), indium oxide-tin oxide containing silicon or silicon oxide, indium oxide-zinc oxide, tungsten oxide, indium oxide containing zinc oxide, graphene, and the like. In addition thereto, gold (Au), platinum (Pt), a nitride of a metallic material (for example, titanium nitride), and the like may be given.
description.heading: (Hole-Injecting Layer)
description.p: The hole-injecting layer is a layer containing a substance having a high hole-injecting property. As such a substance having a high hole-injecting property, molybdenum oxide, titanium oxide, vanadium oxide, rhenium oxide, ruthenium oxide, chromium oxide, zirconium oxide, hafnium oxide, tantalum oxide, silver oxide, tungsten oxide, manganese oxide, an aromatic amine compound, or a polymer compound (oligomers, dendrimers, polymers, etc.) can be given.
description.heading: (Hole-Transporting Layer)
description.p: The hole-transporting layer is a layer containing a substance having a high hole-transporting property. For the hole-transporting layer, an aromatic amine compound, a carbazole derivative, an anthracene derivative, or the like can be used. A polymer compound such as poly(N-vinylcarbazole) (abbreviation: PVK) and poly(4-vinyltriphenylamine) (abbreviation: PVTPA) can also be used. However, substances other than the above-described substances may be used as long as they have a hole-transporting property higher than an electron-transporting property. It should be noted that the layer containing the material having a high hole-transporting property may be formed into not only a monolayer, but also a stacked layer in which two or more layers formed each of the above-described materials are stacked.
description.heading: (Guest (Dopant) Material for Emitting Layer)
description.p: The emitting layer is a layer containing a substance having a high emitting property, and can be formed of varioussubstances. For example, as the substance having a high emitting property, a fluorescent compound which emits fluorescence and a phosphorescent compound which emits phosphorescence can be used. The fluorescent compound is a compound which can emit from a singlet excited state, and the phosphorescent compound is a compound which can emit from a triplet excited state.

As a blue fluorescent emitting material which can be used for an emitting layer, pyrene derivatives, styrylamine derivatives, chrysene derivatives, fluoranthene derivatives, fluorene derivatives, diamine derivatives, triarylamine derivatives, and the like may be given. As a green fluorescent emitting material which can be used for an emitting layer, aromatic amine derivatives and the like may be given. As a red fluorescent emitting material which can be used for an emitting layer, tetracene derivatives, diamine derivatives and the like may be given.

As a blue phosphorescent emitting material which can be used for an emitting layer, metal complexes such as iridium complexes, osmium complexes, platinum complexes and the like may be given. As a green phosphorescent emitting material which can be used for an emitting layer, iridium complexes and the like may be given. As a red phosphorescent emitting material which can be used for an emitting layer, metal complexes such as iridium complexes, platinum complexes, terbium complexes, europium complexes and the like may be given.
description.heading: (Host Material for Emitting Layer)
description.p: The emitting layer may have a constitution in which the above-mentioned substance having a high emitting property (guest material) is dispersed in another substance (host material). As a substance for dispersing the substance having a high emitting property, a variety of substances can be used, and it is preferable to use a substance which has a lowest unoccupied orbital level (LUMO level) higher than that of the substance having a high emitting property, and a highest occupied orbital level (HOMO level) lower than the substance having a high emitting property.

As a substance (host material) for dispersing a substance having a high emitting property, 1) metal complexes such as aluminum complexes, beryllium complexes, and zinc complexes, 2) heterocyclic compounds such as oxadiazole derivatives, benzimidazole derivatives, and phenanthroline derivatives, 3) fused aromatic compounds such as carbazole derivatives, anthracene derivatives, phenanthrene derivatives, pyrene derivatives, and chrysene derivatives, and 4) aromatic amine compounds such as triarylamine derivatives and condensed polycyclic aromatic amine derivatives are used.
description.heading: (Electron-Transporting Layer)
description.p: An electron-transporting layer is a layer containing a substance having high electron-transporting property. For the electron-transporting layer, 1) metal complexes such as aluminum complexes, beryllium complexes, zinc complexes, or the like; 2) heteroaromatic complexes such as imidazole derivatives, benzimidazole derivatives, azine derivatives, carbazole derivatives, phenanthroline derivatives, or the like; and 3) polymer compounds can be used.

In one embodiment of the invention, the electron-transporting layer may or may not contain other substances described above in addition to the first organic compound and the second organic compound described above.
description.heading: (Electron-Injecting Layer)
description.p: An electron-injecting layer is a layer containing a substance having a high electron-injecting property. For the electron-injecting layer, lithium (Li), ytterbium (Yb), lithium fluoride (LiF), cesium fluoride (CsF), calcium fluoride (CaF2), metal complex compounds such as 8-hydroxyquinolinolato-lithium (Liq); alkali metal, alkaline earth metals and a compound thereof such as lithium oxide (LiOx) can be used.
description.heading: (Cathode)
description.p: For the cathode, metals, alloys, electrically conductive compounds, mixtures thereof, and the like which have a small work function (specifically, 3.8 eV or smaller) are preferably used. Specific examples of the cathode material include elements belonging to Group 1 or Group 2 of the Periodic Table of the Elements, i.e., alkali metals such as lithium (Li) and cesium (Cs), alkaline earth metals such as magnesium (Mg), calcium (Ca) and strontium (Sr), and alloys containing these metals (e.g., MgAg and AlLi); rare earth metals such as europium (Eu) and ytterbium (Yb), and alloys containing these metals.

The cathode is usually formed by a vacuum vapor deposition process or a sputtering method. Further, in the case of using a silver paste or the like, a coating method, an inkjet method, or the like can be employed.

Moreover, when the electron-injecting layer is provided, the cathode may be formed of a material selected from various electrically conductive materials such as aluminum, silver, ITO, graphene, indium oxide-tin oxide containing silicon or silicon oxide, regardless of large or small of the work function.

The thickness of each layer is not particularly limited, but is generally preferable that the thickness be in the range of several nm to 1 μm, in order to suppress defects such as pinholes, to decrease applied voltage to be low, and to increase luminous efficiency.

The mixed powder according to one aspect of the invention can be used for a vapor deposition process, and can be applied to any technical field including film formation by vapor deposition of an organic compound.
In one embodiment, the mixed powder is an organic semiconductor material, e.g., a material for an organic EL device, a material for an organic transistor, or a material for an organic solar cell.

In one embodiment, the first organic compound and the second organic compound are both organic semiconductor materials, e.g., materials for an organic EL device, materials for an organic transistor, or materials for an organic solar cell.
As described in the method of depositing according to one aspect of the invention, the first organic compound and the second organic compound are different compounds from each other.

The expression “the first organic compound and the second organic compound are different compounds from each other” includes a case in which their chemical structural formulas (skeletons) are different from each other, and a case in which their chemical structural formulas (skeletons) are the same but contain a different isotope. The “isotope” means an atom having the same in their atomic number but different in the number of neutrons. For example, benzene (C6H6) and deuterated benzene (C6D6) are different components from each other.

In the case where their chemical structural formulas (skeletons) are the same but contain a different isotope, the compounds are also different in a case where just the number or position of the isotope is different from each other. For example, even in deuterated benzene, C6H5D1 and C6D6 are compounds different from each other because the number of isotopes is different. For example, even among compounds represented by C6H4D2, a compound having deuterium atoms at positions 1 and 2 of a benzene ring and a compound having deuterium atoms at positions 1 and 3 of a benzene ring are compounds different from each other because the position of isotopes is different.

description.heading: EXAMPLES
description.p: Now, Examples according to the invention will be described. The invention is not limited in any way by these Examples.
Compounds used in Examples and Comparative Examples are shown below.

Conditions for the method of measuring a spread angle θ of a vapor deposition trajectory is as follows. Conditions not described below are as described above.

After completion of vapor deposition, the mask was removed, and by using the step film thickness meter (surface roughness measuring instrument (SURFCORDER), manufactured by Kosaka Laboratory Ltd.), the height of the steps (film thickness) formed by the mask was measured from the center of the substrate toward the longitudinal direction. FIG. 3 is a schematic diagram of masks 201 placed on the surface of the substrate 102 to be vapor-deposited. description.p: Vapor deposition was performed using a mixed powder obtained by mixing a powder of the compound A with a powder of the compound B whose spread of the vapor deposition trajectory is smaller than that of the compound A, and it was confirmed that the spread of the vapor deposition trajectory of the mixed powder was smaller than that of the compound A.
description.heading: Definition
description.p: In this specification, a hydrogen atom includes its isotopes different in the number of neutrons, namely, a protium, a deuterium and a tritium.

In this specification, at a bondable position in a chemical formula where a symbol such as “R”, or “D” representing a deuterium atom is not indicated, a hydrogen atom, that is, a protium atom, a deuterium atom or a tritium atom is bonded.

In this specification, the number of ring carbon atoms represents the number of carbon atoms forming a subject ring itself among the carbon atoms of a compound having a structure in which atoms are bonded in a ring form (for example, a monocyclic compound, a fused ring compound, a cross-linked compound, a carbocyclic compound, or a heterocyclic compound). When the subject ring is substituted by a substituent, the carbon contained in the substituent is not included in the number of ring carbon atoms. The same shall apply to “the number of ring carbon atoms” described below, unless otherwise specified. For example, a benzene ring has 6 ring carbon atoms, a naphthalene ring includes 10 ring carbon atoms, a pyridine ring includes 5 ring carbon atoms, and a furan ring includes 4 ring carbon atoms. Further, for example, a 9,9-diphenylfluorenyl group includes 13 ring carbon atoms, and a 9,9′-spirobifluorenyl group includes 25 ring carbon atoms.

When a benzene ring is substituted by, for example, an alkyl group as a substituent, the number of carbon atoms of the alkyl group is not included in the number of ring carbon atoms of the benzene ring. Therefore, the number of ring carbon atoms of the benzene ring substituted by the alkyl group is 6. When a naphthalene ring is substituted by, for example, an alkyl group as a substituent, the number of carbon atoms of the alkyl group is not included in the number of ring carbon atoms of the naphthalene ring. Therefore, the number of ring carbon atoms of the naphthalene ring substituted by the alkyl group is 10.

In this specification, the number of ring atoms represents the number of atoms forming a subject ring itself among the atoms of a compound having a structure in which atoms are bonded in a ring form (for example, the structure includes a monocyclic ring, a fused ring and a ring assembly) (for example, a monocyclic compound, a fused ring compound, a cross-linked compound, a carbocyclic compound and a heterocyclic compound). The number of ring atoms does not include atoms which do not form the ring (for example, a hydrogen atom which terminates a bond of the atoms forming the ring), or atoms contained in a substituent when the ring is substituted by the substituent. The same shall apply to “the number of ring atoms” described below, unless otherwise specified. For example, the number of atoms of a pyridine ring is 6, the number of atoms of a quinazoline ring is 10, and the number of a furan ring is 5. For example, hydrogen atoms bonded to a pyridine ring and atoms constituting a substituent substituted on the pyridine ring are not included in the number of ring atoms of the pyridine ring. Therefore, the number of ring atoms of a pyridine ring with which a hydrogen atom or a substituent is bonded is 6. For example, hydrogen atoms and atoms constituting a substituent which are bonded with a quinazoline ring is not included in the number of ring atoms of the quinazoline ring. Therefore, the number of ring atoms of a quinazoline ring with which a hydrogen atom or a substituent is bonded is 10.

In this specification, “XX to YY carbon atoms” in the expression “a substituted or unsubstituted ZZ group including XX to YY carbon atoms” represents the number of carbon atoms in the case where the ZZ group is unsubstituted by a substituent, and does not include the number of carbon atoms of a substituent in the case where the ZZ group is substituted by the substituent. Here, “YY” is larger than “XX”, and “XX” means an integer of 1 or more and “YY” means an integer of 2 or more.

In this specification, “XX to YY atoms” in the expression “a substituted or unsubstituted ZZ group including XX to YY atoms” represents the number of atoms in the case where the ZZ group is unsubstituted by a substituent, and does not include the number of atoms of a substituent in the case where the ZZ group is substituted by the substituent. Here, “YY” is larger than “XX”, and “XX” means an integer of 1 or more and “YY” means an integer of 2 or more.

In this specification, the unsubstituted ZZ group represents the case where the “substituted or unsubstituted ZZ group” is a “ZZ group unsubstituted by a substituent”, and the substituted ZZ group represents the case where the “substituted or unsubstituted ZZ group” is a “ZZ group substituted by a substituent”.

In this specification, a term “unsubstituted” in the case of “a substituted or unsubstituted ZZ group” means that hydrogen atoms in the ZZ group are not substituted by a substituent. Hydrogen atoms in a term “unsubstituted ZZ group” are a protium atom, a deuterium atom, or a tritium atom.

In this specification, a term “substituted” in the case of “a substituted or unsubstituted ZZ group” means that one or more hydrogen atoms in the ZZ group are substituted by a substituent. Similarly, a term “substituted” in the case of “a BB group substituted by an AA group” means that one or more hydrogen atoms in the BB group are substituted by the AA group.

The number of ring atoms of the “unsubstituted heterocyclic group” described in this specification is 5 to 50, preferably 5 to 30, and more preferably 5 to 18, unless otherwise specified.
The number of carbon atoms of the “unsubstituted alkyl group” described in this specification is 1 to 50, preferably 1 to 20, and more preferably 1 to 6, unless otherwise specified.

“Substituted or Unsubstituted Heterocyclic Group”

The “heterocyclic group” described in this specification is a ring group having at least one hetero atom in the ring atom. Specific examples of the hetero atom include a nitrogen atom, an oxygen atom, a sulfur atom, a silicon atom, a phosphorus atom, and a boron atom.
The “heterocyclic group” in this specification is a monocyclic group or a fused ring group.

Specific examples of the “substituted heterocyclic group” include a group in which a hydrogen atom of “unsubstituted heterocyclic group” of the following specific example group G2A is substituted by a substituent, the substituted heterocyclic groups of the following specific example group G2B, and the like. It should be noted that the examples of the “unsubstituted heterocyclic group” and the examples of the “substituted heterocyclic group” enumerated in this specification are mere examples, and the “substituted heterocyclic group” described in this specification includes groups in which hydrogen atom bonded with a ring atom of the heterocyclic group itself in the “substituted heterocyclic group” of the specific example group G2B is further substituted by a substituent, and a group in which hydrogen atom of a substituent in the “substituted heterocyclic group” of the specific example group G2B is further substituted by a substituent.

“Substituted or Unsubstituted Fluoroalkyl Group”

The “substituted or unsubstituted fluoroalkyl group” described in this specification is a group in which at least one hydrogen atom bonded with a carbon atom constituting the alkyl group in the “substituted or unsubstituted alkyl group” is substituted by a fluorine atom, and includes a group in which all hydrogen atoms bonded with a carbon atom constituting the alkyl group in the “substituted or unsubstituted alkyl group” are substituted by a fluorine atom (a perfluoro group). The number of carbon atoms of the “unsubstituted fluoroalkyl group” is 1 to 50, preferably 1 to 30, more preferably 1 to 18, unless otherwise specified in this specification. The “substituted fluoroalkyl group” means a group in which one or more hydrogen atoms of the “fluoroalkyl group” are substituted by a substituent. The “substituted fluoroalkyl group” described in this specification also includes a group in which one or more hydrogen atoms bonded with a carbon atom of the alkyl chains in the “substituted fluoroalkyl group” are further substituted by a substituent, and a group in which one or more hydrogen atom of a substituent in the “substituted fluoroalkyl group” are further substituted by a substituent. Specific examples of the “unsubstituted fluoroalkyl group” include a group in which one or more hydrogen atoms in the “alkyl group” (specific group G3) are substituted by a fluorine atom, and the like.
“Substituted or Unsubstituted Haloalkyl Group”

The “substituted or unsubstituted haloalkyl group” described in this specification is a group in which at least one hydrogen atom bonded with a carbon atom constituting the alkyl group in the “substituted or unsubstituted alkyl group” is substituted by a halogen atom, and also includes a group in which all hydrogen atoms bonded with a carbon atom constituting the alkyl group in the “substituted or unsubstituted alkyl group” are substituted by a halogen atom. The number of carbon atoms of the “unsubstituted haloalkyl group” is 1 to 50, preferably 1 to 30, more preferably 1 to 18, unless otherwise specified in this specification. The “substituted haloalkyl group” means a group in which one or more hydrogen atoms of the “haloalkyl group” are substituted by a substituent. The “substituted haloalkyl group” described in this specification also includes a group in which one or more hydrogen atoms bonded with a carbon atom of the alkyl chain in the “substituted haloalkyl group” are further substituted by a substituent, and a group in which one or more hydrogen atoms of a substituent in the “substituted haloalkyl group” are further substituted by a substituent. Specific examples of the “unsubstituted haloalkyl group” include a group in which one or more hydrogen atoms in the “alkyl group” (specific example group G3) are substituted by a halogen atom, and the like. A haloalkyl group is sometimes referred to as an alkyl halide group.

“The Case where Bonded with Each Other to Form a Ring”

In this specification, the case where “one or more sets of adjacent two or more form a substituted or unsubstituted monocycle by bonding with each other, form a substituted or unsubstituted fused ring by bonding with each other, or do not bond with each other” means the case where “one or more sets of adjacent two or more form a substituted or unsubstituted monocycle by bonding with each other”; the case where “one or more sets of adjacent two or more form a substituted or unsubstituted fused ring by bonding with each other”; and the case where “one or more sets of adjacent two or more do not bond with each other.”

The case where “one or more sets of adjacent two or more form a substituted or unsubstituted monocycle by bonding with each other” and the case where “one or more sets of adjacent two or more form a substituted or unsubstituted fused ring by bonding with each other” in this specification (these cases may be collectively referred to as “the case where forming a ring by bonding with each other”) will be described below. The case of an anthracene compound represented by the following general formula (TEMP-103) in which the mother skeleton is an anthracene ring will be described as an example.

For example, in the case where “one or more sets of adjacent two or more among R921 to R930 form a ring by bonding with each other”, the one set of adjacent two includes a pair of R921 and R922, a pair of R922 and R923, a pair of R923 and R924, a pair of R924 and R930, a pair of R930 and R925, a pair of R925 and R926, a pair of R926 and R927, a pair of R927 and R928, a pair of R928 and R929, and a pair of R929 and R921.

The “one or more sets” means that two or more sets of the adjacent two or more sets may form a ring at the same time. For example, R921 and R922 form a ring QA by bonding with each other, and at the same, time R925 and R926 form a ring QB by bonding with each other, the anthracene compound represented by the general formula (TEMP-103) is represented by the following general formula (TEMP-104).

The case where the “set of adjacent two or more” form a ring includes not only the case where the set (pair) of adjacent “two” is bonded with as in the above-mentioned examples, but also the case where the set of adjacent “three or more” are bonded with each other. For example, it means the case where R921 and R922 form a ring QA by bonding with each other, and R922 and R923 form a ring QC by bonding with each other, and adjacent three (R921, R922 and R923) form rings by bonding with each other and together fused to the anthracene mother skeleton. In this case, the anthracene compound represented by the general formula (TEMP-103) is represented by the following general formula (TEMP-105). In the following general formula (TEMP-105), the ring QA and the ring QC share R922.

The “monocycle” or “fused ring” formed may be a saturated ring or an unsaturated ring, as a structure of the formed ring alone. Even when the “one pair of adjacent two” forms a “monocycle” or a “fused ring”, the “monocycle” or the “fused ring” may form a saturated ring or an unsaturated ring. For example, the ring QA and the ring QB formed in the general formula (TEMP-104) are independently a “monocycle” or a “fused ring.” The ring QA and the ring QC formed in the general formula (TEMP-105) are “fused ring.” The ring QA and ring QC of the general formula (TEMP-105) are fused ring by fusing the ring QA and the ring QC together. When the ring QA of the general formula (TEMP-104) is a benzene ring, the ring QA is a monocycle. When the ring QA of the general formula (TEMP-104) is a naphthalene ring, the ring QA is a fused ring.

The “unsaturated ring” includes, in addition to an aromatic hydrocarbon ring and an aromatic heterocycle, an aliphatic hydrocarbon ring with an unsaturated bond, i.e., double and/or triple bonds in the ring structure (e.g., cyclohexene, cyclohexadiene, etc.), and a non-aromatic heterocycle with an unsaturated bond (e.g., dihydropyran, imidazoline, pyrazoline, quinolizine, indoline, isoindoline, etc.). The “saturated ring” includes an aliphatic hydrocarbon ring without an unsaturated bond and a non-aromatic heterocycle without an unsaturated bond.
Specific examples of the aromatic hydrocarbon ring include a structure in which the group listed as a specific example in the specific example group G1 is terminated by a hydrogen atom.
Specific examples of the aromatic heterocycle include a structure in which the aromatic heterocyclic group listed as a specific example in the example group G2 is terminated by a hydrogen atom.
Specific examples of the aliphatic hydrocarbon ring include a structure in which the group listed as a specific example in the specific example group G6 is terminated by a hydrogen atom.

The term “to form a ring” means forming a ring only with plural atoms of the mother skeleton, or with plural atoms of the mother skeleton and one or more arbitrary atoms in addition. For example, the ring QA shown in the general formula (TEMP-104), which is formed by bonding R921 and R922 with each other, is a ring formed from the carbon atom of the anthracene skeleton with which R921 is bonded, the carbon atom of the anthracene skeleton with which R922 is bonded, and one or more arbitrary atoms. For example, in the case where the ring QA is formed with R921 and R922, when a monocyclic unsaturated ring is formed with the carbon atom of the anthracene skeleton with which R921 is bonded, the carbon atom of the anthracene skeleton with which R922 is bonded, and four carbon atoms, the ring formed with R921 and R922 is a benzene ring.

Here, the “arbitrary atom” is preferably at least one atom selected from the group consisting of a carbon atom, a nitrogen atom, an oxygen atom, and a sulfur atom, unless otherwise specified in this specification. In the arbitrary atom (for example, a carbon atom or a nitrogen atom), a bond which does not form a ring may be terminated with a hydrogen atom or the like, or may be substituted with “arbitrary substituent” described below. When an arbitrary atom other than a carbon atom is contained, the ring formed is a heterocycle.

The number of “one or more arbitrary atom(s)” constituting a monocycle or a fused ring is preferably 2 or more and 15 or less, more preferably 3 or more and 12 or less, and still more preferably 3 or more and 5 or less, unless otherwise specified in this specification.
The “monocycle” is preferable among the “monocycle” and the “fused ring”, unless otherwise specified in this specification.
The “unsaturated ring” is preferable among the “saturated ring” and the “unsaturated ring”, unless otherwise specified in this specification.
Unless otherwise specified in this specification, the “monocycle” is preferably a benzene ring.
Unless otherwise specified in this specification, the “unsaturated ring” is preferably a benzene ring.

Unless otherwise specified in this specification, when “one or more sets of adjacent two or more” are “bonded with each other to form a substituted or unsubstituted monocycle” or “bonded with each other to form a substituted or unsubstituted fused ring”, this specification, one or more sets of adjacent two or more are preferably bonded with each other to form a substituted or unsubstituted “unsaturated ring” from plural atoms of the mother skeleton and one or more and 15 or less atoms which is at least one kind selected from a carbon atom, a nitrogen atom, an oxygen atom, and a sulfur atom.

The substituent in the case where the above-mentioned “monocycle” or “fused ring” has a substituent is, for example, an “arbitrary substituent” described below. Specific examples of the substituent which the above-mentioned “monocycle” or “fused ring” has include the substituent described above in the “Substituent described in this specification” section.

The substituent in the case where the above-mentioned “saturated ring” or “unsaturated ring” has a substituent is, for example, an “arbitrary substituent” described below. Specific examples of the substituent which the above-mentioned “monocycle” or “fused ring” has include the substituent described above in the “Substituent described in this specification” section.

The foregoing describes the case where “one or more sets of adjacent two or more form a substituted or unsubstituted monocycle by bonding with each other” and the case where “one or more sets of adjacent two or more form a substituted or unsubstituted fused ring by bonding with each other” (the case where “forming a ring by bonding with each other”).
Substituent in the Case of “Substituted or Unsubstituted”

In one embodiment in this specification, the substituent (in this specification, sometimes referred to as an “arbitrary substituent”) in the case of “substituted or unsubstituted” is, for example, a group selected from the group consisting of:
an unsubstituted alkyl group including 1 to 50 carbon atoms,
an unsubstituted alkenyl group including 2 to 50 carbon atoms,
an unsubstituted alkynyl group including 2 to 50 carbon atoms,
an unsubstituted cycloalkyl group including 3 to 50 ring carbon atoms,
a halogen atom, a cyano group, a nitro group,
an unsubstituted aryl group including 6 to 50 ring carbon atoms, and
an unsubstituted heterocyclic group including 5 to 50 ring atoms,
wherein, R901 to R907 are independently
a hydrogen atom,
a substituted or unsubstituted alkyl group including 1 to 50 carbon atoms,
a substituted or unsubstituted cycloalkyl group including 3 to 50 ring carbon atoms,
a substituted or unsubstituted aryl group including 6 to 50 ring carbon atoms, or
a substituted or unsubstituted heterocyclic group including 5 to 50 ring atoms.
When two or more R901's are present, the two or more R901's may be the same as or different from each other.
When two or more R902's are present, the two or more R902's may be the same as or different from each other.
When two or more R903's are present, the two or more R903's may be the same as or different from each other.
When two or more R904's are present, the two or more R904's may be the same as or different from each other.
When two or more R905's are present, the two or more R905's may be the same as or different from each other.
When two or more R906's are present, the two or more R906's may be the same as or different from each other.
When two or more R907's are present, the two or more R907's may be the same as or different from each other.
In one embodiment, the substituent in the case of “substituted or unsubstituted” is a group selected from the group consisting of:
an alkyl group including 1 to 50 carbon atoms,
an aryl group including 6 to 50 ring carbon atoms, and
a heterocyclic group including 5 to 50 ring atoms.
In one embodiment, the substituent in the case of “substituted or unsubstituted” is a group selected from the group consisting of:
an alkyl group including 1 to 18 carbon atoms,
an aryl group including 6 to 18 ring carbon atoms, and
a heterocyclic group including 5 to 18 ring atoms.
Specific examples of each of the arbitrary substituents include specific examples of substituent described in the section “Substituent described in this specification” above.

Unless otherwise specified in this specification, adjacent arbitrary substituents may form a “saturated ring” or an “unsaturated ring”, preferably form a substituted or unsubstituted saturated 5-membered ring, a substituted or unsubstituted saturated 6-membered ring, a substituted or unsubstituted unsaturated 5-membered ring, or a substituted or unsubstituted unsaturated 6-membered ring, more preferably form a benzene ring.

Unless otherwise specified in this specification, the arbitrary substituent may further have a substituent. The substituent which the arbitrary substituent further has is the same as that of the above-mentioned arbitrary substituent.

In this specification, the numerical range represented by “AA to BB” means the range including the numerical value AA described on the front side of “AA to BB” as the lower limit and the numerical value BB described on the rear side of “AA to BB” as the upper limit.

In this specification, the numerical range represented by “AA≥BB” means that the numerical value AA is equal to or greater than the numerical value BB, and “AA≤BB” that the numerical value AA is equal to or less than the numerical value BB.

Several embodiments and/or examples of the present invention have been described in detail above. However, without substantially departing from novel teachings and effects of the present invention, the person skilled in the art can readily make a number of modifications to the embodiments and/or examples which are exemplifications of these teachings and effects. Thus, these modifications are included in the scope of the present invention.
